</div></div><div class="content"><h1>Who Discovered Cholera?</h1><p class="cat gray"><strong>Posted In</strong>: <a href="http://discovery.yukozimo.com/category/diseases/" title="View all posts in Diseases">Diseases</a>. <a href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300&amp;pubid=ra-51570ba744ef354e" class="addthis_button atb" rel="nofollow"><img width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif"></a><script src="//s7.addthis.com/js/300/addthis_widget.js#pubid=ra-51570ba744ef354e" type="text/javascript"></script></p><div class="imglf rg ads">
<script async src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>
<!-- Ads Side 250 -->
<ins class="adsbygoogle"
     style="display:inline-block;width:250px;height:250px"
     data-ad-client="ca-pub-1698790680615083"
     data-ad-slot="9358611569"></ins>
<script>
(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script>
</div><p>The bacterium named <a href="http://microbewiki.kenyon.edu/index.php/Vibrio_cholerae">Vibrio cholerae</a> is known to be the microorganism causing the deadly disease called as cholera. The first successful isolation of the Vibrio cholerae bacterium occurs as an important instance in the history of medicine on the whole. It is rather very tough to ascertain who actually discovered cholera. The reasons are not far to seek. Most people attribute the discovery of cholera to Robert Koch, the famous German scientist. However, most interestingly, thirty years before, an Italian scientist named <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filippo_Pacini">Filippo Pacini</a> had actually isolated the bacterium causing cholera.</p><div class="imglf"><a href="http://discovery.yukozimo.com/media/o/3293-1.jpg" target="_blank"><img title="Filippo Pacini and Robert Koch" alt="Filippo Pacini and Robert Koch" src="http://discovery.yukozimo.com/media/t/3293-1.jpg" width="250" height="168" /></a><span>Filippo Pacini discovered the bacteria 30 years before Robert Koch did.</span></div><p><strong>The origins of the word cholera</strong></p><p>Back in the old days, medical experts attributed the excess secretion of bile in human body as the cause of cholera. Interestingly, the word cholera is a derivative of the Greek word “choler” meaning bile. As new scientific methods and tools evolved in 1800s, new theories and observations sprang up and medical experts started looking for new answers. In the 19<sup>th</sup> century, the Dartmouth Electron Microscope Facility released Vibrio cholera in the public domain. During this time, there was a deadly outbreak of cholera pandemic in the Asian region.</p><p><strong>How Filippo Pacini got involved?</strong></p><p>As the disease arrived in Italy, Filippo Pacini began conducting autopsies on the corpses of cholera victims. He closely examined the mucosa or the inner lining of the intestine and could successfully isolate a comma shaped bacillus. This he named as Vibrio. In 1854, Pacini’s results were officially published under the title, “Microscopic observation and pathological deductions on cholera”. However, for many years lahe intestine and could successfully isolate a comma shaped baciter, this paper was not given any importance.</p><p><strong>How Robert Koch got involved?</strong></p><p>Without knowing anything about the results published by Pacini, <a href="http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1905/koch-bio.html">Robert Koch</a>, one of the significant personalities in the microbiology arena started researching on the microorganisms that were causing cholera. Analyzing the samples collected from the cholera victims in Alexandria, Egypt, Robert Koch independently discovered a bacillus, the same that Pacini discovered years back. There was a lapse of thirty years between these two instances of discovery of cholera causing bacteria.</p><p><strong>Credit given, 82 years later</strong></p><p>Robert Koch isolated the bacterium suspected to cause cholera and developed a culture of them, though the culture could not be pure. None of the animals infected by the bacterium contracted cholera. He concluded that animals, unlike humans, were immune to cholera. The studies conducted by Robert Koch could be successful only when he could evolve a pure culture of Vibrio cholera in 1965. He was credited with the discovery of the cholera causing bacteria. However, the earlier efforts of Pacini were rewarded by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Commission_on_Zoological_Nomenclature">the International Committee on Zoological Nomenclature</a>, by naming the cholera causing bacteria as Vibrio Cholerae Pacini 1854. This happened 82 years after Pacini’s death.</p><div class="adsw clear">
